<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lycogaster</taxonomicName>
Shuckard, 1841: 121; 
<bibRefCitation author="Weinstein, P" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="141" pageNumber="142" pagination="399 - 433" title="The host relationships of trigonalyid wasps (Hymenoptera: Trigonalyidae), with a review of their biology and catalogue to world species." url="10.1080/00222939100770281" volume="25" year="1991">Weinstein and Austin 1991</bibRefCitation>
: 414; 
<bibRefCitation author="Carmean, D" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="138" pageNumber="139" pagination="35 - 76" title="Phylogenetic revision of the parasitoid wasp family Trigonalidae (Hymenoptera)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" volume="23" year="1998">Carmean and Kimsey 1998</bibRefCitation>
: 61. Type species (by original designation): 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster pullatus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pullatus">Lycogaster pullatus</taxonomicName>
Shuckard, 1841.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Body length 5.5-15.0 mm; antenna with 22-24 segments, of ♀ widened medially (Fig. 111, but hardly so in 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster angustula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustula">Lycogaster angustula</taxonomicName>
sp. n.); antenna of ♂ without tyloids; supra-antennal elevations small, without depression dorsally (Figs 110, 121, 132, 146); vertex convex and shiny; mandibular condyli close to level of eyes (Figs 113, 122, 135, 149); apical segment of labial palp widened and obtuse, more or less triangular (Fig. 122); metanotum smooth, shiny and weakly convex (Figs 114, 123, 136, 150); triangular dorso-apical part of hind trochanter separated by an oblique groove; fore trochanter subparallel-sided and distinctly longer than hind trochanter; hind tarsus slightly or not modified; basal half of third metasomal sternite with a posteriorly steep, smooth and complete transverse ledge (Figs 118, 129, 140; may be partly hidden under second sternite and rather low in 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster violaceipennis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violaceipennis">Lycogaster violaceipennis</taxonomicName>
); second sternite with pair of small triangular teeth on apical protuberance (Fig. 118; but only with pair of lobe-shaped flaps in male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster violaceipennis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violaceipennis">Lycogaster violaceipennis</taxonomicName>
) and sometimes absent; epipleura of tergites laterally strongly pigmented; fifth sternite of ♀ distinctly emarginate medio-posteriorly (Fig. 118).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="biology">
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
In the New World reared as hyperparasitoid of 
<taxonomicName family="Ichneumonidae" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="family">Ichneumonidae</taxonomicName>
in caterpillars of the families 
<taxonomicName family="Saturniidae" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="family">Saturniidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Notodontidae" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="family">Notodontidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Carmean, D" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="138" pageNumber="139" pagination="35 - 76" title="Phylogenetic revision of the parasitoid wasp family Trigonalidae (Hymenoptera)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" volume="23" year="1998">Carmean and Kimsey 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The record from 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Eumeninae">Eumeninae</taxonomicName>
nests probably concerns prey caterpillars that have been infested with both 
<taxonomicName family="Ichneumonidae" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="family">Ichneumonidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Trigonalyidae" lsidName="" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="family">Trigonalyidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
It is clear from the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Magretti, P" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova" pageId="139" pageNumber="140" pagination="308 - 326" title="Viaggio di Leonardo Fea in Birmania e regione Vicine. LXXIV. Imenotteri. Parte seconda. Trigonalidi, Betilidi, Crisidi colla descrizione di parecchie nuove specie." volume="17" year="1897">Magretti 1897</bibRefCitation>
) and from the redescription of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schulz, WA" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova (Ser. 3)" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" pagination="23 - 37" title="Die Trigonaloiden des Genueser Naturhistorischen Museums." volume="4" year="1908">Schulz (1908)</bibRefCitation>
that 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster rufiventris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufiventris">Lycogaster rufiventris</taxonomicName>
(Magretti, 1897) from Myanmar was correctly assigned to the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lycogaster</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schulz, WA" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova (Ser. 3)" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" pagination="23 - 37" title="Die Trigonaloiden des Genueser Naturhistorischen Museums." volume="4" year="1908">Schulz (1908)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bischoff, H" journalOrPublisher="Hymenopterorum Catalogus" pageId="137" pageNumber="138" pagination="1 - 18" title="Trigonaloidae." volume="5" year="1938">Bischoff (1938)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Weinstein, P" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="141" pageNumber="142" pagination="399 - 433" title="The host relationships of trigonalyid wasps (Hymenoptera: Trigonalyidae), with a review of their biology and catalogue to world species." url="10.1080/00222939100770281" volume="25" year="1991">Weinstein and Austin (1991)</bibRefCitation>
. It has the medial third of the fore wing dark brown as 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster flavonigrata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavonigrata">Lycogaster flavonigrata</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Shuckard, 1841" authorityName="Shuckard" authorityYear="1841" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Lycogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lycogaster nigralva" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigralva">Lycogaster nigralva</taxonomicName>
, but differs by the entire reddish metasoma, the absence of distinct separate teeth besides finely dentate lamelliform protuberance of second sternite and the distinctly convex vertex. The interpretation by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carmean, D" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="138" pageNumber="139" pagination="35 - 76" title="Phylogenetic revision of the parasitoid wasp family Trigonalidae (Hymenoptera)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00042.x" volume="23" year="1998">Carmean and Kimsey (1998</bibRefCitation>
; based on specimens from central and southern India and retaining this species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1835" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Trigonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trigonalys" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trigonalys</taxonomicName>
) seems to be incorrect considering the redescription of the holotype female by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schulz, WA" journalOrPublisher="Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova (Ser. 3)" pageId="140" pageNumber="141" pagination="23 - 37" title="Die Trigonaloiden des Genueser Naturhistorischen Museums." volume="4" year="1908">Schulz (1908)</bibRefCitation>
and the distribution of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1835" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1835" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Trigonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trigonalys" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trigonalys</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
